  "body": "Are there limits on requests via a faucet?\r\nPer [previous proposal](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/pull/18105#), we apparently can't add a few minutes grace period that would allow for regular consistency within human error, on a basis (the connection still doesn't make sense to me) referring to bots.  \r\n\r\nI recently observed the Rinkeby faucet awarding payouts to the same address several times in quick succession, which seemed a bit against the intended spirit:\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/563406/60841742-8b92be00-a1a0-11e9-8113-7d29de10f8d9.png)\r\n\r\nSome copy and paste from the recent logs:\r\n  | 0x508710f58b70ebbea0cfb1b27b59fd859e7be744 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x508710f58b70ebbea0cfb1b27b59fd859e7be744 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x508710f58b70ebbea0cfb1b27b59fd859e7be744 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x508710f58b70ebbea0cfb1b27b59fd859e7be744 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 3 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | 2 minutes ago\r\n  | 0x4b6c775a9cb3200433420ffaec1e574553072508 | a minute ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a minute ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a minute ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a minute ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a minute ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a minute ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0xdf57a505dba37f11460089f2b6bfcccc1b0f959e | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0xffaa853b505e372eb60eee017bd3497a8168799e | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x87b3acf160cd6147193f9220a014611c9e8015e6 | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x3f46d43bc11211f5fee72ed37cdf448b96fd590b | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x3f46d43bc11211f5fee72ed37cdf448b96fd590b | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x3f46d43bc11211f5fee72ed37cdf448b96fd590b | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x3f46d43bc11211f5fee72ed37cdf448b96fd590b | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x3f46d43bc11211f5fee72ed37cdf448b96fd590b | a few seconds ago\r\n  | 0x3f46d43bc11211f5fee72ed37cdf448b96fd590b | a few seconds ago\r\n\r\nI suspect the same human is behind all of these, except the two one-offs.\r\n\r\nI checked 0x508710f58b70ebbea0cfb1b27b59fd859e7be744 which drew 67 times so far today.  3 days ago, the account drew 71 times and then [pulled out](https://rinkeby.etherscan.io/tx/0x9b63e2d15a06fbd6b395e1aef2948a4476cc787f4d7927377ab444edddd3149c) 2,701 ETH to [this account](https://rinkeby.etherscan.io/address/0xdf977109f7e37bd73bf9a8e4ca5ced1f61e04551), which seems to be collecting quite a bit from the others as well. It's amassed >20K ETH in under 10 days!  In doing so, it joins a [long list of accounts](https://rinkeby.etherscan.io/accounts) with balances just over 20K, including other targets where funds from this facuet-drawing account [have been sent](https://rinkeby.etherscan.io/txs?a=0x508710f58b70ebbea0cfb1b27b59fd859e7be744&f=2), directly or indirectly.\r\n\r\nIs there a desire to limit faucet transactions by address and medium?  (E.g. for a given address, only one Twitter post and if desired, also one Facebook post, is honored before the \"you must wait\" note is triggered?)\r\nIf not, and simply having more posts with an address is a great way to circumvent rate-limiting, why be so [strict](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/pull/18105#) about the fractional milliseconds?  \r\n\r\nOf course, even adding this limit wouldn't block whomever is doing this; they would just have to use a wider variety of ETH addresses in the faucet draw step before aggregation.  However, observing this behavior really seems to weaken the case for rejecting the other [PR](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/pull/18105#).",
